So, on one hand, we have these intuitions which come very quickly and naturally, and our brain clearly produces those.

25:27.460 --> 25:32.460
I mean, those are internal. Those are properties of our heads.

25:32.460 --> 25:37.460
When I say we think as a community, I'm referring to a deliberative process, right?

25:37.460 --> 25:40.460
I love the word deliberation because it has these two meanings.

25:40.460 --> 25:47.460
One meaning is that we're thinking things through slowly, but the more common meaning is the sense of a jury

25:47.460 --> 25:49.460
deliberating, right? A group of people.

25:49.460 --> 25:56.460
So, I would argue that right now there are thoughts that are being produced by this group of people collaboratively

25:56.460 --> 25:59.460
that no individual brain would be able to produce.

25:59.460 --> 26:07.460
And even in the domain of memory, right, our memories are shaped by our schema as any good cognitive psychologist knows.

26:07.460 --> 26:12.460
And those schema are social entities, I think, to a large degree.

26:12.460 --> 26:18.460
I'm struck with the fact that in this context, you know, the New York Psycho-Atlantic Institute,

26:18.460 --> 26:23.460
1940, the highest of the high, we're having this kind of discussion.

26:23.460 --> 26:32.460
It seems to me the more appropriate discussion for the Atlantic Institute is why didn't we try to base this on an empirical level?

26:32.460 --> 26:40.460
Why didn't we go to the trouble as, in fact, the American Psycho-Analysts before the European Evasion of Arpurn, Chris and Lowensley were about to do,

26:40.460 --> 26:44.460
Larry, Cuba, et cetera, to try to test some of these ideas?

26:44.460 --> 26:52.460
How come psychoanalysis has been so ineffective in trying to test these ideas in a more rigorous way?

26:52.460 --> 27:00.460
Why isn't an imaging facility associated with every analytic institute, why isn't there a full-time research program associated with each institute?

27:00.460 --> 27:07.460
Here a great institute, like the New York Psycho-Analysts Institute, doesn't have a full-time research effort going on.

27:07.460 --> 27:20.460
I spoke here about ten years ago and I made a comment like this and he said, you must realize every person who's trained here must spend at least two hours a week learning about imaging.

27:20.460 --> 27:29.460
But you know what, they can learn in two hours a week about imaging, but I know about Greek philosophy, even less.

27:29.460 --> 27:32.460
Yes, well, I'm asking you.

27:32.460 --> 27:36.460
This three of us are collecting data on this issue.

27:36.460 --> 27:38.460
Knowledge in the concrete context.

27:38.460 --> 27:46.460
I'm not here as a representative of the New York Psycho-Analysts, so I can't answer it as the way New York Psycho-Analytics would do,

27:46.460 --> 27:54.460
but I would say that 30 years ago, nobody would have invited you to give you a talk to the ten years ago.

27:54.460 --> 28:06.460
Because 30 years ago, there was a conviction that what we thought and how we saw our theory explained everything, or at least explained the problems we were talking about.

28:06.460 --> 28:09.460
I didn't for a moment, 30 years ago think so.

28:09.460 --> 28:10.460
Who didn't?

28:10.460 --> 28:11.460
I didn't.

28:11.460 --> 28:12.460
No, I'm sure you didn't.

28:12.460 --> 28:13.460
I'm not sure.

28:13.460 --> 28:14.460
I'm not sure.

28:14.460 --> 28:15.460
I'm not sure.

28:15.460 --> 28:17.460
So what we did was we did the psychoanalysts.

28:17.460 --> 28:29.460
So when I was training here, there was no question that what the teachers told us, and then we developed our connected ideas about that, that we had a lot of answers.

28:29.460 --> 28:31.460
And that's how we work with the patients.

28:31.460 --> 28:42.460
I think the question for psychoanalysis that is relevant is if some of that knowledge, some of that those findings from Freud on,

28:42.460 --> 28:45.220
what Freud said came from his head. There was no...

28:45.220 --> 28:45.940
Most of it.

28:45.940 --> 28:46.860
Right.

28:46.860 --> 28:51.380
So, if that wasn't right,

28:51.380 --> 28:55.860
or if that now is proven to not fit the data,

28:55.860 --> 28:58.340
how come our patients are doing well?

28:58.340 --> 29:01.460
Psychoanalysis has helped a lot of patients.

29:01.460 --> 29:03.540
So, what is it that makes it,

29:03.540 --> 29:05.740
and that's the question I have for myself,

29:05.740 --> 29:10.020
is what is the therapeutic action of what we do?

29:10.020 --> 29:10.860
It's not...

29:10.860 --> 29:11.700
You don't know that.

29:11.700 --> 29:12.540
No.

29:12.540 --> 29:14.060
You don't know what is related to interpretation.

29:14.060 --> 29:16.700
You don't know whether it's just being present with a person.

29:16.700 --> 29:20.140
I mean, there are so many variables that are involved here.

29:20.140 --> 29:20.780
You know...

29:20.780 --> 29:21.580
But it's certainly...

29:21.580 --> 29:23.660
Mary and Rudolph Goldberg are always telling me recently

29:23.660 --> 29:27.020
she's trying out a situation which, in an analytic situation,

29:27.020 --> 29:28.500
rather than sitting behind the patient,

29:28.500 --> 29:30.540
she's sitting in front of the patient.

29:30.540 --> 29:32.460
Finds it in some circumstance, it works better.

29:32.460 --> 29:34.980
There's so many things that haven't been looked at.

29:34.980 --> 29:37.460
It's a surprisingly...

29:37.460 --> 29:40.860
unquestioning field.

29:40.860 --> 29:42.860
Aren't you flogging a dead horse here?

29:42.860 --> 29:43.700
I'm sorry.

29:43.700 --> 29:44.620
Aren't you flogging a dead horse?

29:44.620 --> 29:46.380
I mean, haven't we all moved on to that?

29:46.380 --> 29:50.620
Well, maybe it can be resuscitated if we rethink it.

29:50.620 --> 29:53.100
But I think we learn a great deal

29:53.100 --> 29:55.780
by seeing why did people turn away from that?

29:55.780 --> 29:59.020
Why did they do what was clear to so many of us?

29:59.020 --> 30:01.220
And that is to ask them direct questions.

30:03.660 --> 30:09.340
I think, Eric, there is a certain arrogance of scientists

30:09.340 --> 30:14.260
that the scientific way to know is the only way.

30:14.260 --> 30:16.660
There is evidence, and then you know the truth.

30:16.660 --> 30:19.780
I happen to be a scientist, so I share that.

30:19.780 --> 30:25.620
We should know that the concept of knowing is contested.

30:25.620 --> 30:29.020
There are many people who know that Jesus lives

30:29.020 --> 30:31.180
beyond a reasonable doubt.

30:31.180 --> 30:33.260
And so there are just other ways.

30:33.260 --> 30:35.540
There is revelation and transmission

30:35.540 --> 30:38.060
and many other ways of knowing.

30:38.060 --> 30:40.100
And science is one religion.

30:40.100 --> 30:42.700
I happen to be part of it.

30:42.700 --> 30:45.140
But we should really not...

30:45.140 --> 30:48.060
But don't you think one of our functions

30:48.060 --> 30:51.540
is to help people see and what circumstances.

30:51.540 --> 30:54.380
Science might be helpful to moving them further.

30:54.380 --> 30:57.140
I mean, certainly the science...

30:57.140 --> 31:00.220
So you have Eric coming along and saying,

31:00.220 --> 31:03.260
I've discovered cognitive behavior therapy.

31:03.260 --> 31:06.740
It's so much more useful in these circumstances.

31:06.740 --> 31:08.500
Why not do a systematic study to see

31:08.500 --> 31:10.860
in what circumstances cognitive behavior?

31:10.860 --> 31:14.420
I mean, you're not asking me because, of course, I agree with you.

31:14.420 --> 31:16.740
At the point, I think...

31:16.740 --> 31:18.820
LAUGHTER

31:18.820 --> 31:20.140
The point?

31:20.140 --> 31:21.740
I mean...

31:21.740 --> 31:23.860
That's it. That's it.

31:23.860 --> 31:25.140
It's not.

31:25.140 --> 31:28.660
Because most people know things differently,

31:28.660 --> 31:30.100
and they think they know.

31:30.100 --> 31:31.300
How far is this?

31:31.300 --> 31:32.980
As academics.

31:32.980 --> 31:34.340
Is to help people see...

31:34.340 --> 31:34.900
I mean, you're not...

31:34.900 --> 31:37.260
What is the better way to go?

31:37.260 --> 31:39.660
What I'm suggesting, actually,

31:39.660 --> 31:44.980
is that if the function of academics is to convince people

31:44.980 --> 31:49.060
of the value of science and to help them see the value of science,

31:49.060 --> 31:52.020
then it would be a good idea to have some empathy

31:52.020 --> 31:55.060
for what people think they know now

31:55.060 --> 31:56.980
in different ways of know.

31:56.980 --> 32:00.180
We have to start from an attempt to understand

32:00.180 --> 32:02.980
and to empathize with other ways of knowing.

32:02.980 --> 32:05.540
I'd add to that, it's great, I think what you're saying,

32:05.540 --> 32:09.140
if I'm understanding correctly, is A, have empathy for that,

32:09.140 --> 32:11.460
but also have a scientific understanding

32:11.460 --> 32:14.820
of what gives us that subjective feeling of knowledge.

32:14.820 --> 32:16.580
Absolutely. And how to help people

32:16.580 --> 32:19.300
move from their current position to another one.

32:19.300 --> 32:23.060
So this is a topic close to my heart.

32:23.060 --> 32:25.540
I wrote a book some 10 years ago called Fear of Knowledge,

32:25.540 --> 32:26.100
which discusses...

32:26.100 --> 32:26.660
Fear of what?

32:26.660 --> 32:27.700
Fear of knowledge.

32:27.700 --> 32:29.180
Knowledge. Fear of knowledge.

32:29.180 --> 32:31.380
LAUGHTER

32:31.380 --> 32:32.820
Fear of knowledge.

32:32.820 --> 32:38.260
Which was precisely about, so you just said something.

32:38.260 --> 32:39.780
You did actually a classic maneuver,

32:39.780 --> 32:43.860
which you said something extremely radical.

32:43.860 --> 32:46.980
And then you backpedaled to something much more innocuous

32:46.980 --> 32:48.100
that everybody could accept.

32:48.100 --> 32:50.900
And Stanley Fish, by the way, does exactly the same thing.

32:50.900 --> 32:52.820
I wouldn't have thought you would be in that company.

32:52.820 --> 32:59.380
But the radical remark is science is just one religion among many.

32:59.380 --> 33:02.780
OK. This is an amazing thing.

33:02.780 --> 33:05.700
OK. It's not even ultimately a coherent view,

33:05.700 --> 33:09.380
because if you say, well, you know, I happen to be a scientist,

33:09.380 --> 33:10.820
you know, that's my favorite method.

33:10.820 --> 33:12.100
But other people have other methods.

33:12.100 --> 33:14.140
For instance, they use tea leaves,

33:14.140 --> 33:17.740
or they use alleged divine revelation,

33:17.740 --> 33:19.860
and so forth to find out what's true.

33:19.860 --> 33:21.420
That's, of course, perfectly fine.

33:21.420 --> 33:22.180
That's their method.

33:22.180 --> 33:23.620
I mean, did I say that's perfectly fine?

33:23.620 --> 33:25.140
Well, you said science.

33:25.140 --> 33:26.140
You said science.

33:26.140 --> 33:26.700
You said science.

33:26.700 --> 33:28.300
I did not imply.

33:28.300 --> 33:30.620
Science is one religion among many.

33:30.620 --> 33:31.220
Yes.

33:31.220 --> 33:32.820
Yes, I did say that.

33:32.820 --> 33:38.100
The way we treat religions, because we don't treat them

33:38.100 --> 33:40.900
necessarily as a source of truth, is we say people

33:40.900 --> 33:43.620
are entitled to their faith, to their religious beliefs.

33:43.620 --> 33:44.620
OK.

33:44.620 --> 33:47.540
I, OK.

33:47.540 --> 33:49.580
The innocuous remark is, no, look.

33:49.580 --> 33:52.300
Of course, this is a privileged way of figuring out

33:52.300 --> 33:53.100
what's true.

33:53.100 --> 33:55.860
But in order to bring other people around,

33:55.860 --> 33:56.900
you have to have empathy.

33:56.900 --> 34:00.220
You have to understand what shoes they're walking in.

34:00.220 --> 34:04.580
You have to see something essential, which

34:04.580 --> 34:06.620
is that from the point of view of somebody

34:06.620 --> 34:09.140
who doesn't believe in science, and that's

34:09.140 --> 34:13.220
at least 30% of Americans, if not more,

34:13.220 --> 34:16.980
from their point of view, science is just another religion.

34:16.980 --> 34:20.420
And it's useful to understand that when we are talking

34:20.420 --> 34:24.860
to people who do not share our basic beliefs about what

34:24.860 --> 34:27.500
is true and how to acquire truth, we better

34:27.500 --> 34:29.540
try to understand who we're talking to.

34:29.540 --> 34:31.220
Empathy is no question.

34:31.220 --> 34:34.340
But leveling it all out by saying it's just one religion.

34:34.340 --> 34:36.860
No, I mean, I wasn't leveling it all out.

34:36.860 --> 34:39.420
I was really trying to tell you that there

34:39.420 --> 34:41.020
is another perspective.

34:41.020 --> 34:42.620
Of course, there's no other perspective.

34:42.620 --> 34:45.300
Other perspective, science is a religion.

34:45.300 --> 34:46.060
Like, no.

34:46.060 --> 34:47.060
No.

34:47.060 --> 34:48.060
No.

34:48.060 --> 34:49.060
No.

34:49.060 --> 34:50.260
What is the definition of that?

34:50.260 --> 34:51.900
A miracle.

34:51.900 --> 34:53.180
And science, what definition is a miracle.

34:53.180 --> 34:55.300
It's a system of belief.

34:55.300 --> 34:57.900
But there are different systems of belief.

34:57.900 --> 35:00.260
I keep expecting you to ask them to explain this.

35:00.260 --> 35:01.260
Yes.

35:01.260 --> 35:03.060
That's right.

35:03.060 --> 35:04.860
It's a strong belief.

35:04.860 --> 35:06.700
It's too much fun.

35:06.700 --> 35:07.900
And I doubt that they could.

35:11.100 --> 35:15.100
But humans aren't the only species

35:15.100 --> 35:18.220
that have false confidence and false knowledge.

35:18.220 --> 35:19.900
So we have to also take into account

35:19.900 --> 35:22.180
that much of this is probably emerging

35:22.180 --> 35:24.380
from basic biological mechanisms.

35:24.380 --> 35:26.900
We see you can get animals to have false confidence

35:26.900 --> 35:28.180
and false beliefs as well.

35:28.180 --> 35:30.700
I don't know how much is known about the social sharing

35:30.700 --> 35:31.900
of knowledge.

35:31.900 --> 35:33.500
But certainly, there are studies showing

35:33.500 --> 35:36.340
these sort of phenomena emerge in non-humans as well.

35:36.340 --> 35:38.540
I think that's a really important aspect

35:38.540 --> 35:40.180
in terms of understanding what I think,

35:40.180 --> 35:41.220
partly what you were referring to,

35:41.220 --> 35:45.660
is the physical and biological manifestations and mechanisms.

35:45.660 --> 35:47.100
And there's a big danger there if you

35:47.100 --> 35:50.740
take the rational context of, I have rational information,

35:50.740 --> 35:53.540
so I'm going to understand that.

35:53.540 --> 35:56.020
The most beautiful way I ever heard this expressed,

35:56.020 --> 35:57.820
I spent a lot of time talking to Gerald Edelman

35:57.820 --> 36:01.340
about selective systems in nature.

36:01.340 --> 36:03.900
And we believe it or not, we compared.

36:03.900 --> 36:07.420
He first talked about his mind theory.

36:07.420 --> 36:10.420
But I said, can we go back to something empirical?

36:10.420 --> 36:13.980
And can we go to your work on immune response?

36:13.980 --> 36:16.660
Because he had found the structure of the antibody.

36:16.660 --> 36:19.260
And so we had these great talks about comparing a magician

36:19.260 --> 36:23.900
and his audience doing tricks that could adapt, not stage tricks,

36:23.900 --> 36:26.180
but tricks where you're adapting very quickly,

36:26.180 --> 36:29.020
almost like three card monty on the street.

36:29.020 --> 36:32.620
So there's a very feedback and feedback for the response.

36:32.620 --> 36:35.780
So I was trying to explain this concept of selective processes

36:35.780 --> 36:39.900
in nature and at a Mind Science Foundation conference.

36:39.900 --> 36:42.940
And there's a philosopher and a cognitive psychologist.

36:42.940 --> 36:44.220
And it wasn't happening.

36:44.220 --> 36:47.380
And then a wonderful woman, the Secretary of the Mind Science

36:47.380 --> 36:50.340
Foundation, she came by and I said,

36:50.340 --> 36:52.660
well, let's put it in terms of nightclubs.

36:52.660 --> 36:54.820
So this is getting into how does this information

36:54.820 --> 36:56.220
get specific, right?

36:56.220 --> 36:58.860
So if you're thinking about, does it have to be rational?

36:58.860 --> 37:01.380
So I said, well, let's think about nightclubs

37:01.380 --> 37:03.980
because at the time I was working at a big nightclub in New York.

37:03.980 --> 37:05.980
And I said, so if you walked into nightclubs,

37:05.980 --> 37:07.220
she was in her 20s.

37:07.220 --> 37:09.500
And I said, if you walked into a nightclub, you'd ignore me.

37:09.500 --> 37:10.340
And she said, no.

37:10.340 --> 37:13.220
I'd find out if you were an owner or a friend of the owner.

37:13.220 --> 37:16.180
And if you weren't, then I'd ignore you.

37:16.180 --> 37:20.660
So I said, OK, this is the level of reality I want to address.

37:20.660 --> 37:22.540
So then I tried to explain this idea of selection

37:22.540 --> 37:24.260
of the selection of processes in nature.

37:24.260 --> 37:26.860
And she said, it's so obvious what he's saying.

37:26.860 --> 37:28.180
And the other people got it.

37:28.180 --> 37:29.020
What are you talking about?

37:29.020 --> 37:32.740
Because they kept on trying to fit it into a rational construct.

37:32.740 --> 37:35.300
And she said, listen, when I go to a nightclub

37:35.300 --> 37:38.780
at the beginning of the night, I know exactly who I'm looking

37:38.780 --> 37:40.060
for.

37:40.060 --> 37:41.700
I'm looking for Mr. Wright.

37:41.700 --> 37:44.460
But by the end of the night, when it's closing time,

37:44.460 --> 37:46.820
I'm looking for Mr. Wright now.

37:46.820 --> 37:53.380
And all he's saying is that nature can never choose.

37:53.380 --> 37:54.540
It can't deliberate.

37:54.540 --> 37:57.140
It can only select, in terms of natural selection.

37:57.140 --> 37:59.180
She didn't say that a minute, a minute.

37:59.180 --> 38:01.020
The Mr. Wright now.

38:01.020 --> 38:04.780
So once we shift from these areas of cognitive constructs,

38:04.780 --> 38:07.820
of cognitive information, and go to this animal stuff,

38:07.820 --> 38:10.220
it's good to think about ourselves in different contexts

38:10.220 --> 38:12.300
where we can appreciate selective processes

38:12.300 --> 38:14.940
and nature a little more easily.

38:14.940 --> 38:16.860
Yeah, no, I'm sure that's right.

38:16.860 --> 38:20.660
But I do think that there's a special status

38:20.660 --> 38:23.180
given to certain kinds of constructs

38:23.180 --> 38:25.340
that only humans are capable of.

38:25.340 --> 38:28.340
Yvall Harari has this great thought experiment.

38:28.340 --> 38:32.380
He asks you to imagine 50,000 chimpanzees

38:32.380 --> 38:35.940
sitting in the stadium watching a soccer match.

38:35.940 --> 38:37.540
Pure chaos, right?

38:37.540 --> 38:38.660
Complete chaos.

38:38.660 --> 38:41.140
You'd have animals jumping all over each other.

38:41.140 --> 38:43.980
There's something that humans are capable of.

38:43.980 --> 38:47.820
There's a way that humans can interact with other humans

38:47.820 --> 38:50.340
that no other, I'll go this far,

38:50.340 --> 38:53.700
that no other cognitive mechanism is capable of.

38:53.700 --> 38:56.460
My joke, my quick response is I say,

38:56.460 --> 38:58.380
we've come into a point in society

38:58.380 --> 39:02.340
where we really believe that Mr. Spock must run the enterprise.

39:02.340 --> 39:06.700
And in, because in other words,

39:06.700 --> 39:08.780
the sense of reason must lead.

39:08.780 --> 39:11.380
And then we forget the reason why a morality play

39:11.380 --> 39:12.900
called Star Trek was written

39:12.900 --> 39:15.100
to show the importance of our humanity.

39:15.100 --> 39:17.540
So all I'm saying is it's really, it's,

39:17.540 --> 39:20.540
I was not saying that we are led by reason.

39:20.540 --> 39:24.260
I was saying that we are able to collaborate

39:24.260 --> 39:27.940
as a group, as a community,

39:27.940 --> 39:32.460
in a way that no other cognitive systems can.

39:32.460 --> 39:33.540
That's the claim.

39:33.540 --> 39:37.380
So one thing we can do is share each other's intentionality.

39:37.380 --> 39:39.820
And Mike Thomasella has great arguments

39:39.820 --> 39:42.460
showing that no other animal, no other machine

39:42.460 --> 39:45.460
is capable of sharing intentionality with others.

39:45.460 --> 39:47.820
And that is the whole Captain Kirk point, right?

39:47.820 --> 39:49.660
If you can build a collective group

39:49.660 --> 39:52.540
that can do things beyond individual capacity.

39:54.540 --> 39:55.860
Steve, I had a question.

39:55.860 --> 40:00.140
When you wrote your book, I'm sure, before Trump's election.

40:00.140 --> 40:00.980
Yes.

40:02.780 --> 40:04.420
The idea of a community,

40:04.420 --> 40:07.540
could there be two communities that do not communicate

40:07.540 --> 40:08.380
with each other?

40:08.380 --> 40:11.100
I mean, would you be writing the same book today?

40:12.060 --> 40:16.100
Oh, well, I'd have a lot more examples

40:16.100 --> 40:17.380
if I were writing it today.

40:17.380 --> 40:20.220
But yes, the ideas would be the same.

40:20.220 --> 40:21.940
So one of our ideas is this notion

40:21.940 --> 40:23.460
of contagious understanding, right?

40:23.460 --> 40:27.020
We run experiments showing that when other people

40:27.020 --> 40:30.820
feel they understand, then you feel you understand more, right?

40:30.820 --> 40:32.700
Understanding's a bit like a disease.

40:32.700 --> 40:34.340
It's sort of, it's contagious.

40:35.340 --> 40:39.900
And as a result of that, you can have ideological communities

40:39.900 --> 40:42.500
where individuals think they understand

40:42.500 --> 40:44.180
because the people around them understand,

40:44.180 --> 40:45.540
but everybody else understands

40:45.540 --> 40:47.460
because the people around them understand

40:47.460 --> 40:49.840
and there's no actual understanding.

40:51.300 --> 40:54.180
So when you have that kind of dynamic,

40:54.180 --> 40:56.540
